# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-american
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:african-american/african-american-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:african-american/african-american-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:african-american/scissor] While all scissors largely follow the same working principle, heavy-duty scissors intended for cutting tough materials tend to be called shears instead of scissors (e.g. pruning shears and grass shears), and some larger, two-handed implements are called *trimmers* instead (e.g. hedge trimmer).
[src:african-american/scissor] Choosing the optimal type of scissors/shears is crucial, as otherwise it can cause unwanted damage to the target material and/or the instrument itself.
[src:african-american/scissor] Surgical scissors, used to divide tissues and trim/reshape implants during surgical operations, have even a greater variety to deal with different anatomical and procedural circumstances.
[src:african-american/scissor] Most scissors have a ringed handle to allow readily opening for repeated cutting, and some even have spring between the shanks to assist opening (especially for shears with straight handle).
[src:african-american/scissor] While historically inexpensive, mass-produced scissors often have bare metal handles, modern scissors are often designed ergonomically with composite thermoplastic and rubber covering on handles, which are more comfortable for the hand.
[src:african-american/scissor] The noun *scissors* is treated as a plural noun and therefore takes a plural verb (e.g., *these scissors are*).
[src:african-american/scissor] Alternatively, the tool is referred to by the singular phrase *a pair of scissors*.
[src:african-american/scissor] The word *shears* is used to describe similar instruments that are larger in size and for heavier cutting.
[src:african-american/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company in Hangzhou, China, has been manufacturing scissors since 1663.
[src:african-american/scissor] Pivoted scissors were not manufactured in large numbers until 1761, when Robert Hinchliffe of Sheffield produced the first pair of modern-day scissors made of hardened and polished cast steel.
[src:african-american/scissor] His major challenge was to form the bows; first, he made them solid, then drilled a hole, and then filed away metal to make this large enough to admit the user's fingers.
[src:african-american/scissor] This process was laborious, and apparently Hinchliffe improved upon it in order to increase production.
[src:african-american/scissor] Hinchliffe lived in Cheney Square (now the site of Sheffield Town Hall), and set up a sign identifying himself as a "fine scissor manufacturer".
[src:african-american/scissor] He achieved strong sales in London and elsewhere.
[src:african-american/scissor] The vast majority of global scissor manufacturing takes place in China.
[src:african-american/scissor] As of 2019, China was responsible for 64.3% of worldwide scissors exports.
[src:african-american/scissor] When combined with Chinese Taipei exports, this rises to 68.3%.
[src:african-american/scissor] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company, founded in 1663, is one of the oldest continuously operating scissor manufacturers in the world.
[src:african-american/scissor] The company was nationalized in 1958 and now employs 1500 people who annually mass-produce an estimated seven million pairs of inexpensive scissors that retail for an average of US$4 each.
[src:african-american/scissor] In the late 14th century, the English word "scissors" came into usage.
[src:african-american/scissor] It was derived from the Old French word *cisoires*, which referred to shears.
[src:african-american/scissor] There are several historically important scissor-producing regions in France: Haute-Marne in Nogent-en Bassigny, Châtellereault, Thiers and Rouen.
[src:african-american/scissor] These towns, like many other scissor-producing communities, began with sabre, sword and bayonet production, which transitioned to scissors and other blades in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:african-american/scissor] Thiers, in the Puy-de-Dôme department of Auvergne, remains an important centre of scissor and cutlery production.
[src:african-american/scissor] It is home to both the Musée de la Coutellerie, which showcases the town's 800-year history of blade-making, as well as Coutellia, an industry tradeshow that advertises itself as one of the largest annual gatherings of artisanal blade-makers in the world.
[src:african-american/scissor] Germany was responsible for manufacturing just under 7% of global scissors exports in 2019.
[src:african-american/scissor] Often called "The City of Blades", Solingen, in North Rhine-Westphalia, has been a center for the manufacturing of scissors since medieval times.
[src:african-american/scissor] At the end of the 18th century it's estimated that there were over 300 scissorsmiths in Solingen.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 1995 the City of Solingen passed The Solingen Ordinance, an update to a 1930s law that decreed "Made in Solingen" stamps could only be applied to products almost entirely manufactured in the old industrial area of Solingen.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 2019 this applied to approximately 150 companies making high-quality blades of all kinds, including scissors.
[src:african-american/scissor] Friedrich Herder, founded in Solingen in 1727, is one of the oldest scissors manufacturers still operating in Germany.
[src:african-american/scissor] Premana, in Lecco Province, has its origins in ironworks and knife manufacturing beginning in the 16th century.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 1900 there were ten scissor manufacturing workshops, 20 in 1952 and 48 by 1960.
[src:african-american/scissor] Today, Consorzio Premax, an industrial partnership, organizes over 60 local companies involved in the manufacture of scissors for global markets.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 2019 Italy exported 3.5% of scissors manufactured globally.
[src:african-american/scissor] One of the oldest Premanese scissor manufacturing firms still in operation is Sanelli Ambrogio, which was founded in 1869.
[src:african-american/scissor] Scissormaking in Japan evolved from sword making in the 14th century.
[src:african-american/scissor] Seki, in Gifu Prefecture, was a renowned center of swordmaking beginning in the 1200s.
[src:african-american/scissor] After citizens were no longer permitted to carry swords, the city's blacksmiths turned to making scissors and knives.
[src:african-american/scissor] There are many specialized types of Japanese scissors, but sewing scissors were introduced by American Commodore Matthew Perry from the United States in 1854.
[src:african-american/scissor] The Sasuke workshop in Sakai City south of Osaka is run by Yasuhiro Hirakawa, a 5th generation scissorsmith.
[src:african-american/scissor] The company has been in operation since 1867.
[src:african-american/scissor] Yasuhiro Hirakawa is the last traditional scissormaker in Japan, making scissors in the traditional style where the blades are believed to be thinner, lighter and sharper than European scissors.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 2018 he was profiled in a documentary that featured a pair of his bonsai snips which retailed for US$35,000.
[src:african-american/scissor] In Solsona, Spain, scissor manufacturing began in the 16th century.
[src:african-american/scissor] At the industry's peak in the 18th century there were 24 workshops, organized as the Guild of Saint Eligius, the patron saint of knife makers.
[src:african-american/scissor] By the mid-1980s there were only two, and by 2021, Pallarès Solsona, founded in 1917 by Lluìs and Carles Pallarès Canal, and still family-operated, was the town's sole remaining artisanal scissor manufacturer.
[src:african-american/scissor] Sheffield was home to the first mass production of scissors beginning in 1761.
[src:african-american/scissor] By the 19th century there were an estimated 60 steel scissor companies in Sheffield.
[src:african-american/scissor] However, since the 1980s, industry globalization and a shift towards cheaper, mass-produced scissors created price deflation that many artisanal manufacturers could not compete with.
[src:african-american/scissor] The Sheffield scissor industry consisted of just two local companies in 2021.
[src:african-american/scissor] The two remaining Sheffield scissor manufacturers are William Whiteley, founded in 1760, and Ernest Wright, which was established in 1902.
[src:african-american/scissor] Both now focus on high-end/niche crafting of "products for life" rather than mass production.
[src:african-american/scissor] Between these two firms it is estimated that there are no more than ten "putter-togetherers" or "putters" who are the master-trained craftspeople responsible for high quality Sheffield scissor assembly.
[src:african-american/scissor] In 2020, Ernest Wright was recognized with the Award for Endangered Crafts by the British Heritage Crafts Association.
[src:african-american/scissor] There are two varieties of left-handed scissors.
[src:african-american/scissor] Many common left-handed scissors (often called "semi"-left-handed scissors) simply have reversed finger grips.
[src:african-american/scissor] The blades open and close as with right-handed scissors, so that users tend to pull the blades apart as they are cutting.
[src:african-american/scissor] This can be challenging for craftspeople as the blades still obscure the cut.
[src:african-american/scissor] "True" left-handed scissors have both reversed finger grips and reversed blade layout, like mirror images of right-handed scissors.
[src:african-american/scissor] A left-handed person accustomed to using semi-left handed scissors may find using true left-handed scissors difficult at first, as they may have learned to rely heavily on the strength of their thumb to pull the blades apart vs. pushing the blades together in order to cut.
[src:african-american/scissor] Some scissors are marketed as ambidextrous.
[src:african-american/scissor] These have symmetric handles so there is no distinction between the thumb and finger handles, and have very strong pivots so that the blades rotate without any lateral give.
[src:african-american/scissor] However, most "ambidextrous" scissors are in fact still right-handed in that the upper blade is on the right, and hence is on the outside when held in the right hand.
[src:african-american/scissor] Even if they cut successfully, the blade orientation will block the view of the cutting line for a left-handed person.
[src:african-american/scissor] True ambidextrous scissors are possible if the blades are double-edged and one handle is swung all the way around (to almost 360 degrees) so that what were the backs of the blades become the new cutting edges.
[src:african-american/scissor] U.S. patent 3,978,584 was awarded for true ambidextrous scissors.
[src:african-american/trouser] The oldest known trousers, dating to the period between the thirteenth and the tenth centuries BC, were found at the Yanghai cemetery in Turpan, Xinjiang (Tocharia), in present-day western China.
[src:african-american/trouser] Made of wool, the trousers had straight legs and wide crotches and were likely made for horseback riding.
[src:african-american/trouser] A pair of trouser-like leggings dating back to 3350 and 3105 BC were found in the Austria–Italy border worn by Ötzi.
[src:african-american/trouser] In most of Europe, trousers have been worn since ancient times and throughout the Medieval period, becoming the most common form of lower-body clothing for adult males in the modern world.
[src:african-american/trouser] Breeches were worn instead of trousers in early modern Europe by some men in higher classes of society.
[src:african-american/trouser] Distinctive formal trousers are traditionally worn with formal and semi-formal day attire.
[src:african-american/trouser] Since the mid-twentieth century, trousers have increasingly been worn by women as well.
[src:african-american/trouser] Jeans, made of denim, are a form of trousers for casual wear widely worn all over the world by people of both genders.
[src:african-american/trouser] Shorts are often preferred in hot weather or for some sports and also often by children and adolescents.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers are worn on the hips or waist and are often held up by buttons, elastic, a belt, or suspenders (braces).
[src:african-american/trouser] Unless elastic, and especially for men, trousers usually provide a zippered or buttoned fly.
[src:african-american/trouser] Jeans usually feature side and rear pockets with pocket openings placed slightly below the waist band.
[src:african-american/trouser] It is also possible for trousers to provide cargo pockets further down the legs.
[src:african-american/trouser] Maintenance of fit is more challenging for trousers than for some other garments.
[src:african-american/trouser] Leg-length can be adjusted with a hem, which helps to retain fit during the adolescent and early adulthood growth years.
[src:african-american/trouser] Tailoring adjustment of girth to accommodate weight gain or weight loss is relatively limited, and otherwise serviceable trousers might need to be replaced after a significant change in body composition.
[src:african-american/trouser] Higher-quality trousers often have extra fabric included in the centre-back seam allowance, so the waist can be let out further.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Scotland, a type of tartan trousers traditionally worn by Highlanders as an alternative to the Great Plaid and its predecessors is called *trews* or in the original Gaelic *triubhas*.
[src:african-american/trouser] This is the source of the English word *trousers*.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trews are still sometimes worn instead of the kilt at ceilidhs, weddings etc.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers are also known as *breeks* in Scots, the cognate of *breeches*.
[src:african-american/trouser] The item of clothing worn under trousers is called *pants*.
[src:african-american/trouser] The standard English form *trousers* is also used, but it is sometimes pronounced in a manner approximately represented by [ˈtruːzɨrz], as Scots did not completely undergo the Great Vowel Shift, and thus retains the vowel sound of the Gaelic *triubhas*, from which the word originates.
[src:african-american/trouser] In North America, Australia, and South Africa, *pants* is the general category term, whereas *trousers* (sometimes *slacks* in Australia and North America) often refers more specifically to tailored garments with a waistband, belt-loops, and a fly-front.
[src:african-american/trouser] In these dialects, elastic-waist knitted garments would be called *pants*, but not *trousers* (or *slacks*).
[src:african-american/trouser] North Americans call undergarments *underwear*, *underpants*, *undies*, or *panties* (the last are women's garments specifically) to differentiate them from other pants that are worn on the outside.
[src:african-american/trouser] The term *drawers* normally refers to undergarments, but in some dialects, may be found as a synonym for *breeches*, that is, trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] In these dialects, the term *underdrawers* is used for undergarments.
[src:african-american/trouser] Many North Americans refer to their underpants by their type, such as *boxers* or *briefs*.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Australia, men's underwear also has various informal terms including *under-dacks*, *undies*, *dacks* or *jocks*.
[src:african-american/trouser] In New Zealand, men's underwear is known informally as *undies* or *dacks*.
[src:african-american/trouser] In India, underwear is also referred to as *innerwear*.
[src:african-american/trouser] The words *trouser* (or *pant*) instead of *trousers* (or *pants*) is sometimes used in the tailoring and fashion industries as a generic term, for instance when discussing styles, such as "a flared trouser", rather than as a specific item.
[src:african-american/trouser] The words *trousers* and *pants* are *pluralia tantum*, nouns that generally only appear in plural form—much like the words *scissors* and *tongs*, and as such *pair of trousers* is the usual correct form.
[src:african-american/trouser] However, the singular form is used in some compound words, such as *trouser-leg*, *trouser-press* and *trouser-bottoms*.
[src:african-american/trouser] Jeans are trousers typically made from denim or dungaree cloth.
[src:african-american/trouser] There are several different main types of pants and trousers, such as dress pants, jeans, khakis, chinos, leggings, overalls, and sweatpants.
[src:african-american/trouser] They can also be classified by fit, fabric, and other features.
[src:african-american/trouser] There is apparently no universal, overarching classification.
[src:african-american/trouser] There is some evidence, from figurative art, of trousers being worn in the Upper Paleolithic, as seen on the figurines found at the Siberian sites of Mal'ta and Buret'.
[src:african-american/trouser] Fabrics and technology for their construction are fragile and disintegrate easily, so often are not among artefacts discovered in archaeological sites.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers enter recorded history in the sixth century BC, on the rock carvings and artworks of Persepolis, and with the appearance of horse-riding Eurasian nomads in Greek ethnography.
[src:african-american/trouser] At this time, Iranian peoples such as Scythians, Sarmatians, Sogdians and Bactrians among others, along with Armenians and Eastern and Central Asian peoples such as the Xiongnu/Hunnu, are known to have worn trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers are believed to have been worn by people of any gender among these early users.
[src:african-american/trouser] The ancient Greeks used the term ἀναξυρίδες (*anaxyrides*) for the trousers worn by Eastern nations and σαράβαρα (*sarabara*) for the loose trousers worn by the Scythians.
[src:african-american/trouser] However, they did not wear trousers since they thought them ridiculous, using the word θύλακοι (*thulakoi*), pl. of θύλακος (*thulakos*) 'sack', as a slang term for the loose trousers of Persians and other Middle Easterners.
[src:african-american/trouser] Republican Rome viewed the draped clothing of Greek and Minoan (Cretan) culture as an emblem of civilization and disdained trousers as the mark of barbarians.
[src:african-american/trouser] As the Roman Empire expanded beyond the Mediterranean basin, however, the greater warmth provided by trousers led to their adoption.
[src:african-american/trouser] Two types of trousers eventually saw widespread use in Rome: the *feminalia*, which fit snugly and usually fell to knee length or mid-calf length, and the *braccae*, loose-fitting trousers that were closed at the ankles.
[src:african-american/trouser] Both garments were adopted originally from the Celts of Europe, although later familiarity with the Persian Near East and the Germanic peoples increased acceptance.
[src:african-american/trouser] *Feminalia* and *braccae* both began use as military garments, spreading to civilian dress later, and were eventually made in a variety of materials, including leather, wool, cotton and silk.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers of various designs were worn throughout the Middle Ages in Europe, especially by men.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers in this period, generally called *braies*, varied in length and were often closed at the cuff or even had attached foot coverings, although open-legged pants were also seen.
[src:african-american/trouser] By the eighth century there is evidence of the wearing in Europe of two layers of trousers, especially among upper-class males.
[src:african-american/trouser] The under layer is today referred to by costume historians as *drawers*, although that usage did not emerge until the late sixteenth century.
[src:african-american/trouser] Over the drawers were worn trousers of wool or linen, which in the tenth century began to be referred to as *breeches* in many places.
[src:african-american/trouser] Tightness of fit and length of leg varied by period, class, and geography.
[src:african-american/trouser] As undergarments, these trousers became briefer or longer as the length of the various medieval outer garments changed, and were met by, and usually attached to, another garment variously called hose or stockings.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the fourteenth century it became common among the men of the noble and knightly classes to connect the hose directly to their pourpoints (the padded under jacket worn with armoured breastplates that would later evolve into the doublet) rather than to their drawers.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the fifteenth century, rising hemlines led to ever briefer drawers until they were dispensed with altogether by the most fashionable elites who joined their skin-tight hose back into trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] These trousers, which we would today call tights but which were still called hose or sometimes joined hose at the time, emerged late in the fifteenth century and were conspicuous by their open crotch which was covered by an independently fastening front panel, the codpiece.
[src:african-american/trouser] The exposure of the hose to the waist was consistent with fifteenth-century trends, which also brought the pourpoint/doublet and the shirt, previously undergarments, into view, but the most revealing of these fashions were only ever adopted at court and not by the general population.
[src:african-american/trouser] Men's clothes in Hungary in the fifteenth century consisted of a shirt and trousers as underwear, and a dolman worn over them, as well as a short fur-lined or sheepskin coat.
[src:african-american/trouser] Hungarians generally wore simple trousers, only their colour being unusual; the dolman covered the greater part of the trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Around the turn of the sixteenth century it became conventional to separate hose into two pieces, one from the waist to the crotch which fastened around the top of the legs, called trunk hose, and the other running beneath it to the foot.
[src:african-american/trouser] The trunk hose soon reached down the thigh to fasten below the knee and were now usually called "breeches" to distinguish them from the lower-leg coverings still called *hose* or, sometimes *stockings*.
[src:african-american/trouser] By the end of the sixteenth century, the codpiece had also been incorporated into breeches which featured a *fly* or *fall front* opening.
[src:african-american/trouser] As a modernization measure, Tsar Peter the Great of Russia issued a decree in 1701 commanding every Russian man, other than clergy and peasant farmers, to wear trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] During the French Revolution of 1789 and following, many male citizens of France adopted a working-class costume including ankle-length trousers, or pantaloons (named from a Commedia dell'Arte character named *Pantalone*) in place of the aristocratic knee-breeches (*culottes*).
[src:african-american/trouser] Pantaloons became fashionable in early nineteenth-century England and the Regency era.
[src:african-american/trouser] The style was introduced by Beau Brummell (1778–1840) and by mid-century had supplanted breeches as fashionable street-wear.
[src:african-american/trouser] At this point, even knee-length pants adopted the open bottoms of trousers (see shorts) and were worn by young boys, for sports, and in tropical climates.
[src:african-american/trouser] Breeches proper have survived into the twenty-first century as court dress, and also in baggy mid-calf (or three-quarter length) versions known as plus-fours or knickers worn for active sports and by young schoolboys.
[src:african-american/trouser] Types of breeches are also still worn today by fencers, baseball and American football players, and by equestrians.
[src:african-american/trouser] Sailors may have played a role in the worldwide dissemination of trousers as a fashion.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, sailors wore baggy trousers known as *galligaskins*.
[src:african-american/trouser] Sailors also pioneered the wearing of jeans – trousers made of denim.
[src:african-american/trouser] These became more popular in the late nineteenth century in the American West because of their ruggedness and durability.
[src:african-american/trouser] Starting around the mid-nineteenth century, Wigan pit-brow women scandalized Victorian society by wearing trousers for their work at the local coal mines.
[src:african-american/trouser] They wore skirts over their trousers and rolled them up to their waists to keep them out of the way.
[src:african-american/trouser] Although pit-brow lasses worked above ground at the pit-head, their task of sorting and shovelling coal involved hard manual labour, so wearing the usual long skirts of the time would have greatly hindered their movements.
[src:african-american/trouser] The Korean word for trousers, *baji* (originally *pajibaji*) first appears in recorded history around the turn of the fifteenth century, but pants may have been in use by Korean society for some time.
[src:african-american/trouser] From at least this time pants were worn by both sexes in Korea.
[src:african-american/trouser] Men wore trousers either as outer garments or beneath skirts, while it was unusual for adult women to wear their pants (termed *sokgot*) without a covering skirt.
[src:african-american/trouser] As in Europe, a wide variety of styles came to define regions, time periods and age and gender groups, from the unlined *gouei* to the padded *sombaji*.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Western society, it was Eastern culture that inspired French designer Paul Poiret (1879–1944) to be one of the first to design pants for women.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 1913, Poiret created loose-fitting, wide-leg trousers for women called harem pants, which were based on the costumes of the popular ballet *Sheherazade*.
[src:african-american/trouser] Written by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov in 1888, Sheherazade was based on a collection of legends from the Middle East called 1001 Arabian Nights.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the early twentieth century, women air pilots and other working women often wore trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Frequent photographs from the 1930s of actresses Marlene Dietrich and Katharine Hepburn in trousers helped make trousers acceptable for women.
[src:african-american/trouser] During World War II, women employed in factories or doing other "men's work" on war service wore trousers when the job demanded it.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the post-war era, trousers became acceptable casual wear for gardening, the beach, and other leisure pursuits.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Britain during World War II the rationing of clothing prompted women to wear their husbands' civilian clothes, including trousers, to work while the men were serving in the armed forces.
[src:african-american/trouser] This was partly because they were seen as practical for work, but also so that women could keep their clothing allowance for other uses.
[src:african-american/trouser] As this practice of wearing trousers became more widespread and as the men's clothing wore out, replacements were needed.
[src:african-american/trouser] By the summer of 1944, it was reported that sales of women's trousers were five times more than the previous year.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 1919, Luisa Capetillo challenged mainstream society by becoming the first woman in Puerto Rico to wear trousers in public.
[src:african-american/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was considered to be a crime, but the charges were later dropped.
[src:african-american/trouser] In the 1960s, André Courrèges introduced long trousers for women as a fashion item, leading to the era of the pantsuit and designer jeans and the gradual erosion of social prohibitions against girls and women wearing trousers in schools, the workplace and in fine restaurants.
[src:african-american/trouser] Charlotte Reid (R-Ill.) became the first woman to wear trousers in the US Congress.
[src:african-american/trouser] Pat Nixon was the first American First Lady to wear trousers in public.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 1989, California state senator Rebecca Morgan became the first woman to wear trousers in a US state senate.
[src:african-american/trouser] Hillary Clinton was the first woman to wear trousers in an official American First Lady portrait.
[src:african-american/trouser] Women were not allowed to wear trousers on the US Senate floor until 1993.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Malawi women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:african-american/trouser] Since 2004 the International Skating Union has allowed women to wear trousers instead of skirts in ice-skating competitions.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2009, journalist Lubna Hussein was fined the equivalent of $200 when a court found her guilty of violating Sudan's decency laws by wearing trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2012 the Royal Canadian Mounted Police began to allow women to wear trousers and boots with all their formal uniforms.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2012 and 2013, some Mormon women participated in "Wear Pants to Church Day", in which they wore trousers to church instead of the customary dresses to encourage gender equality within the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
[src:african-american/trouser] More than one thousand women participated in 2012.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2013, Turkey's parliament ended a ban on women lawmakers wearing trousers in its assembly.
[src:african-american/trouser] The bylaw was originally intended to prevent women from wearing the pantalons fashionable with Parisian rebels in the French Revolution.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2014, an Indian family court in Mumbai ruled that a husband objecting to his wife wearing a kurta and jeans and forcing her to wear a sari amounts to cruelty inflicted by the husband and can be a ground to seek divorce.
[src:african-american/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of the Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:african-american/trouser] Until 2016 some female crew members on British Airways were required to wear British Airways' standard "ambassador" uniform, which has not traditionally included trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2017, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints announced that its female employees could wear "professional pantsuits and dress slacks" while at work; dresses and skirts had previously been required.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2018 it was announced that female missionaries of that church could wear dress slacks except when attending the temple and during Sunday worship services, baptismal services, and mission leadership and zone conferences.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2019, Virgin Atlantic began to allow its female flight attendants to wear trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Pleats located just below the waistband on the front typify many styles of formal and casual trousers, including suit trousers and khakis.
[src:african-american/trouser] There may be one, two, three, or no pleats, which may face either direction.
[src:african-american/trouser] When the pleats open toward the pockets they are called reverse pleats (typical of most trousers today) and when they open toward the fly they are known as forward pleats.
[src:african-american/trouser] In modern trousers, men's models generally have pockets for carrying small items such as wallets, keys or mobile phones, but women's trousers often do not – and sometimes have what are called Potemkin pockets, a fake slit sewn shut.
[src:african-american/trouser] If there are pockets, they are often much smaller than in men's clothes.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2018, journalists at The Pudding found less than half of women's front pockets could fit a thin wallet, let alone a handheld phone and keys.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trouser-makers can finish the legs by hemming the bottom to prevent fraying.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers with turn-ups (cuffs in American English), after hemming, are rolled outward and sometimes pressed or stitched into place.
[src:african-american/trouser] A fly is a covering over an opening join concealing the mechanism, such as a zipper, velcro, or buttons, used to join the opening.
[src:african-american/trouser] In trousers, this is most commonly an opening covering the groin, which makes the pants easier to put on or take off.
[src:african-american/trouser] The opening also allows men to urinate without lowering their trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Trousers have varied historically in whether or not they have a fly.
[src:african-american/trouser] Originally, hose did not cover the area between the legs.
[src:african-american/trouser] This was instead covered by a doublet or by a codpiece.
[src:african-american/trouser] When breeches were worn, during the Regency period for example, they were fall-fronted (or broad fall).
[src:african-american/trouser] Later, after trousers (pantaloons) were invented, the fly-front (split fall) emerged.
[src:african-american/trouser] The panelled front returned as a sporting option, such as in riding breeches, but is now hardly ever used, a fly being by far the most common fastening.
[src:african-american/trouser] Most flies now use a zipper, though button-fly pants continue to be available.
[src:african-american/trouser] At present, most trousers are held up through the assistance of a belt which is passed through the **belt loops** on the waistband of the trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] However, this was traditionally a style acceptable only for casual trousers and work trousers; suit trousers and formal trousers were suspended by the use of braces (*suspenders* in American English) attached to buttons located on the interior or exterior of the waistband.
[src:african-american/trouser] Today, this remains the preferred method of trouser support amongst adherents of classical British tailoring.
[src:african-american/trouser] Many men claim this method is more effective and more comfortable because it requires no cinching of the waist or periodic adjustment.
[src:african-american/trouser] In modern Western society, males customarily wear trousers and not skirts or dresses.
[src:african-american/trouser] There are exceptions, however, such as the ceremonial Scottish kilt and Greek fustanella, as well as robes or robe-like clothing such as the cassocks of clergy and the academic robes, both rarely worn today in daily use.
[src:african-american/trouser] Among certain groups, low-rise, baggy trousers exposing underwear became fashionable; for example, among skaters and in 1990s hip hop fashion.
[src:african-american/trouser] This fashion is called sagging or, alternatively, "busting slack".
[src:african-american/trouser] These groups permit women to wear underpants as long as they are hidden.
[src:african-american/trouser] By contrast, many Muslim sects approve of pants as they are considered more modest than any skirt that is shorter than ankle length.
[src:african-american/trouser] However, some mosques require ankle length trousers for both Muslims and non-Muslims on the premises.
[src:african-american/trouser] The Catholic Pope Nicholas I approved of both men and women wearing pants.
[src:african-american/trouser] The wife was thus granted a divorce on the ground of cruelty as defined under section 27(1)(d) of Special Marriage Act, 1954.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Rome in 1992, a 45-year-old driving instructor was accused of rape.
[src:african-american/trouser] When he picked up an 18-year-old for her first driving lesson, he allegedly raped her for an hour, then told her that if she was to tell anyone he would kill her.
[src:african-american/trouser] Later that night she told her parents and her parents agreed to help her press charges.
[src:african-american/trouser] While the alleged rapist was convicted and sentenced, the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the conviction in 1998 because the victim wore tight jeans.
[src:african-american/trouser] It was argued that she must have necessarily have had to help her attacker remove her jeans, thus making the act consensual ("because the victim wore very, very tight jeans, she had to help him remove them...and by removing the jeans...it was no longer rape but consensual sex").
[src:african-american/trouser] The court stated in its decision "it is a fact of common experience that it is nearly impossible to slip off tight jeans even partly without the active collaboration of the person who is wearing them." This ruling sparked widespread feminist protest.
[src:african-american/trouser] The day after the decision, women in the Italian Parliament protested by wearing jeans and holding placards that read "Jeans: An Alibi for Rape".
[src:african-american/trouser] As a sign of support, the California Senate and Assembly followed suit.
[src:african-american/trouser] Soon Patricia Giggans, executive director of the Los Angeles Commission on Assaults Against Women, (now Peace Over Violence) made Denim Day an annual event.
[src:african-american/trouser] As of 2011 at least 20 U.S. states officially recognize Denim Day in April.
[src:african-american/trouser] Wearing jeans on this day, 22 April, has become an international symbol of protest.
[src:african-american/trouser] In 2008 the Supreme Court of Cassation overturned the ruling, so there is no longer a "denim" defense to the charge of rape.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Malawi, women were not legally allowed to wear trousers under President Kamuzu Banda's rule until 1994.
[src:african-american/trouser] Capetillo was sent to jail for what was then considered to be a crime, but the judge later dropped the charges against her.
[src:african-american/trouser] In Sudan, Article 152 of the Memorandum to the 1991 Penal Code prohibits the wearing of "obscene outfits" in public.
[src:african-american/trouser] This law has been used to arrest and prosecute women wearing trousers.
[src:african-american/trouser] Thirteen women including journalist Lubna al-Hussein were arrested in Khartoum in July 2009 for wearing trousers; ten of the women pleaded guilty and were flogged with ten lashes and fined 250 Sudanese pounds apiece.
[src:african-american/trouser] Lubna al-Hussein considers herself a good Muslim and asserts "Islam does not say whether a woman can wear trousers or not.
[src:african-american/trouser] But it is insulting." She was eventually found guilty and fined the equivalent of $200 rather than being flogged.
[src:african-american/trouser] In May 2004, in Louisiana, Democrat and state legislator Derrick Shepherd proposed a bill that would make it a crime to appear in public wearing trousers below the waist and thereby exposing one's skin or "intimate clothing".
[src:african-american/trouser] In February 2005, Virginia legislators tried to pass a similar law that would have made punishable by a $50 fine "any person who, while in a public place, intentionally wears and displays his below-waist undergarments, intended to cover a person's intimate parts, in a lewd or indecent manner".
[src:african-american/trouser] (It is not clear whether, with the same coverage by the trousers, exposing underwear was considered worse than exposing bare skin, or whether the latter was already covered by another law.) The law passed in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:african-american/trouser] However, various criticisms to it arose.
[src:african-american/trouser] For example, newspaper columnists and radio talk show hosts consistently said that since most people that would be penalized under the law would be young African-American men, the law would thus be a form of racial discrimination.
[src:african-american/trouser] Virginia's state senators voted against passing the law.
[src:african-american/trouser] In California, Government Code Section 12947.5 (part of the California Fair Employment and Housing Act (FEHA)) expressly protects the right to wear pants.
[src:african-american/trouser] Thus, the standard California FEHA discrimination complaint form includes an option for "denied the right to wear pants".
